🟦 Step 1 — Open the Correct ODBC Administrator
Because Access .mdb is 32‑bit, you must open the 32‑bit ODBC tool, even on a 64‑bit Windows.

Run this:

Code
C:\Windows\SysWOW64\odbcad32.exe
Do not use the one in System32 — that is 64‑bit and will not show your DSN.

🟦 Step 2 — Find the DSN “IFSReport”
Inside the ODBC Administrator:

Go to System DSN (most likely)
or User DSN

Look for an entry named IFSReport

Select it → click Configure

This opens the Oracle ODBC configuration window.

🟦 Step 3 — View the DSN Details
Inside the DSN configuration you will see fields such as:

Data Source Name: IFSReport

Description: (optional)

TNS Service Name / DBQ: e.g., ORCL, IFSDB, PROD, etc.

User ID: (may be blank)

Driver: e.g., Oracle in OraClient12Home1

If it uses a TNS entry, the actual host/port/SID are inside tnsnames.ora.

🟦 Step 4 — If You Need the Full Connection String
Once you open the DSN, you can reconstruct the Access connection string:

Example:

Code
ODBC;DSN=IFSReport;UID=IFSUSER;DBQ=IFSDB;
If Access uses DSN‑less connections, the linked table Connect property will show more details.

🟦 Optional — Extract DSN Info from Linked Tables
In the VBA Immediate Window (ALT+F11 → CTRL+G):

vba
For Each t In CurrentDb.TableDefs
    If t.Connect <> "" Then Debug.Print t.Name & " --> " & t.Connect
Next
This prints the exact connection string Access is using.
